  "summary": "A twin loft bed with a full safety railing, a built-in ladder side, a plywood-and-2x4 platform, and a fire-station-themed front panel with an arched cutout over the ladder opening.",
  "description": "The core structure is a rectangular frame built from 1x3 and 1x8 boards, standing on ten 1x3 legs — build this frame first and get it dead square before adding anything else, since the railing, ladder, and trim all reference it. Four plywood panels (48\" x 9-1/4\") and two more (48\" x 22-1/2\") form the loft platform floor, resting on a pair of 2x4 support beams running the length of the bed, with slats cut at 39-1/2\" filling in the mattress support area.\n\n**The railing is the most repetitive part of the build** — 44 short 1x2 pickets plus 4 wider 1x3 pickets, all cut to the same 15-1/4\" length, installed around every open side of the loft to make it safe to sleep in. Take the time to space these evenly; an uneven railing is the first thing anyone notices about a loft bed.\n\nThree separate trim packages finish the piece: full-side trim (the plain long side), ladder-side trim (the side with rungs built in for climbing up), and front trim — which includes a 1x8 board with an **arch shape cut out with a jigsaw**, the detail that gives this loft its fire-station look, sitting above the ladder opening like an engine bay door. **This is a large, multi-stage build** — work through the frame, platform, railing, ladder, and trim as five distinct phases rather than trying to hold the whole thing in your head at once.",
